textOriginal:
@@alli6840 Look, people tan because of exposure to UV, right? In Canada, the UV index ranges from 0 for much of the  winter to 11 in the summer. In Texas, the UV index in the summer averages 12, but it never gets lower than the 3 range. 

So, in Canada, someone goes from producing next to no melanin to producing 11 times as much. And the *same person* over the course of a year in Texas goes from a mildly sunny winter to a summer that exposes them to 4 times as much radiation, so they produce 4 times as much melanin. So the person in Canada range by more shades of tan than the person in Texas, even if they have exactly the same levels of melanocytes.

And not that it matters at all, but I am indeed a POC.

1st: conditioner NEVER on the top of your head. It will cause problems with your scalp.
2nd: if it is a biodegradable conditioner it will melt in the ocean but it wont pollute. If it isnt biodegradable it will melt in the ocean AND pollute. Not worth it.
3rd: better to have a mask on your hair the night before…that way you give some moist before the beach. Also braid your hair if you plan to go INTO the water, that way tangles are reduce. 
4th: coming from the beach, unbraid UNDER water. Use some deep conditioner first (middle to bottom) to detangle…then take a shower as normal.
If the travel is going to be long, the nightly mask must be a day off so you dont saturate your hair
